[2] Israel (Hula Valley): cranes, epidemiology and control, scientists' views
Date: Fri 7 Jan 2022 05:54 IST
Source: Haaretz [in Hebrew, trans. Mod.AS, edited]
http://www.haaretz.co.il/misc/article-print-page/.premium-MAGAZINE-1.10520867


Prof. Ran Nathan, from the "movement ecology laboratory" at the Hebrew University, felt that something was wrong with the cranes as early as mid-December [2021]. For a decade he has been following them through transmitters that indicate their movements and location. When the avian flu epidemic broke out, 4 of the 10 cranes he was following ceased movement, and the remaining 6 showed alarming signs of a decline in activity levels, a phenomenon he had never seen before. "At that time only 40 deaths among the cranes were observed," he says. "I raised a shout that it was a huge event, and I hope this shout became helpful."

The outbreak -- which killed [in Israel] about 8000 cranes, other birds and more than a million poultry [including culled animals - Mod.AS] -- is unusual by any criteria. Avian influenza has been known for many years, and cases of mass infection and death are known to researchers, but these occur among flocks of chickens and other domestic birds, or in mixed communities of domestic and wild birds. In a flock composed exclusively of wild birds, such an event is very rare. "There has never been such an outbreak, surely not among cranes," says Nathan.

The question is how the virus will behave from now on. Are we back to the beginning of 2020, once again confronting a pandemic? Experts in Israel fear that spring migration will become the main engine for the spread of the virus in the coming months: hundreds of millions of birds returning from Africa to Europe will once again pass through the Hula Valley, catch the virus from other birds, from contaminated ground surface and water, potentially spread it throughout Eurasia. Dr. Ron Elazari-Volcani, a veterinarian at the zoological garden of the Tel Aviv University, warns: "There is a mega-veterinary event here, not only at the national level but also internationally."

The main question at stake today is whether to continue feeding the cranes in the Hula Valley, as has been done for years to keep them limited to this location -- or to stop feeding to reduce the viral load in the Hula Valley ahead of spring, while probably risking a spread of the disease across the country with moving cranes. Nathan says: "We must reach a situation where in mid-February [2022] we are prepared to take care of the infection centers. We have an international responsibility for what happens."

Eleazar-Volcani calls for drastic measures to reduce the risk of a global epidemic, even if these harm the flock of cranes in the Hula. "The health of the migratory flyway passing through the Hula should be prioritized over interests of local chicken coops. This will need securing compensations to the farmers in case affected, while favouring freedom from infection among the huge number of birds that will move northwards from Africa in another 2 months. Feeding them should be stopped in order to decrease their density in the Hula Valley and preventing the breeding of infection. Clearing the area from the virus before spring migration arrives is essential. The disinfection of the contaminated feeding area should be considered. To deter the birds from landing and prevent them from grazing in the area during the spring, the installation of propane cannons or nylon coverage deserve being considered."

The Nature and Parks Authority, on the other hand, believes that there is no justification for stopping the feeding of the cranes, and fears that the infected birds will spread to other parts of the country in search of food. Regarding the consequences of spring migration, Uri Nave from the PA's science division says: "During the spring there will be temperatures where the flu is less aggressive and there is a decrease in morbidity and mortality. It is also a migration with a different pattern -- the birds rush to the nesting sites in Europe and spend less time in Israel."

One of the factors that has influenced the outbreak of the plague is the global change in the migratory pattern of birds in recent decades. The birds' natural habitats disappeared, and humans provided them with new food sources. This is joined by climate change, which has made winters in Europe and the Middle East relatively warm and allowed the flocks to avoid or shorten their journey south.

In the Hula, the change took place following the re-flooding of the reedbed in the 1990s and the shift of farmers in the area from growing cotton to grains such as corn, peanuts and chickpeas, which became food for cranes. With the increased crane population and because many preferred to winter in the country instead of continuing to Africa, the damage caused to farmers also worsened. This is when their feeding venture started.

Experts admit that it is difficult to assess the consequences of the current outbreak, and that the lack of a formula for a perfect balance between bird protection and agricultural protection will make it difficult to prevent similar outbreaks. What remains is to learn how to deal more effectively with their consequences, for example, by systematically collecting carcasses at the center of the disease's outbreak.

"We need one responsible agency who can make decisions," says Dr. Moti Charter of the University of Haifa, who yesterday [6 Jan 2022] documented the carcasses of birds of prey, including owls, falcons and buzzards in the Agamon Hula area. The main concern is the damage to rare birds such as white-tailed eagles, only 2 of which live in the Hula, white-headed ducks, or ferruginous ducks.

The decision regarding the feeding of the cranes will have to be made in the coming months. "I do not know if it is possible to return the genie into the bottle", says Elazari-Vulcani, "it remains only to try to reduce damage."

[Byline: Tzafrir Rinat and Nir Hasson]

